  "summary": "Deletion of enchanting table items",
  "environment_raw": null,
  "description": "When you start enchanting something in an enchanting table, but don t select the enchant and just put the lapis and items in, and you disconnect, or get kicked from a server, the items and lapis gets deleted. n n(on a 1.21.8 server) n n",
  "Steps to Reproduce": "1. Start Minecraft and connect to a server running version 1.21.8.\n2. Ensure you have at least one item (such as a tool or piece of armor) and 1 to 3 Lapis Lazuli in your inventory.\n3. Locate an Enchanting Table in the world or craft one if necessary.\n4. Right-click on the Enchanting Table to open the enchanting interface.\n5. Place the item you want to enchant in the left input slot of the Enchanting Table.\n6. Place 1 to 3 Lapis Lazuli in the designated slot on the right side of the interface.\n7. Do not select any enchantment option that appears on the right side of the GUI.\n8. Disconnect from the server by either using the disconnect option or by being kicked from the server.\n9. Reconnect to the server and check your inventory for the item and Lapis Lazuli you placed in the Enchanting Table.",
  "Environment": "Minecraft Java Edition Version 1.21.8",
  "Observed Behavior": "When a player initiates the enchanting process at an enchanting table by placing an item and 1 to 3 lapis lazuli into the respective slots but does not select any enchantment option, the game enters a state where the enchanting table is ready to apply an enchantment. If the player disconnects from the server or is kicked while in this state, the items placed in the enchanting table, along with the lapis lazuli, are lost permanently. This behavior occurs specifically on servers running version 1.21.8 of Minecraft. \n\nThis issue results in the unintended loss of valuable resources, as players expect their items and lapis lazuli to remain in their inventory or be returned after reconnecting. The bug does not occur if the player selects an enchantment before disconnecting; in such cases, the enchantment process completes as intended, and the items are consumed accordingly. \n\nTo reproduce this bug:\n1. Approach an enchanting table.\n2. Place an item (e.g., a pickaxe) in the left slot.\n3. Insert 1-3 lapis lazuli into the designated slot.\n4. Do not select any enchantment option.\n5. Disconnect from the server or get kicked.\n6. Upon reconnecting, check the inventory to find that the item and lapis lazuli are missing.\n\nThis inconsistency in the enchanting mechanics could lead to frustration among players and disrupt gameplay, emphasizing the need for a fix to ensure that items and resources are preserved during unexpected disconnections.",
  "Expected Behavior": "When a player uses an enchanting table and places items along with lapis lazuli into the slots without selecting an enchantment, the game should retain those items and lapis lazuli even if the player disconnects or is kicked from the server. Upon reconnecting, the player should find the items and lapis lazuli in their inventory, as the enchanting process should not consume resources until an enchantment is actually selected and confirmed. This behavior aligns with Minecraft's intended functionality, where items and resources should only be removed from the player's inventory once the enchanting action is completed.",
